\par }\pard \qj \li1122\ri1034\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin1034\lin1122\itap0\pararsid31649 {\b\i\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649 \'9310.  THAT in reply to paragraph 9 of the affidavit I state that the pr
operties mentioned in 9 above are not my properties and I do not have any interest in them.\'94
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid31649 {\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649 
\par It is }{\insrsid788741\charrsid31649 noteworthy }{\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649 that although Mr. Kasenge avers that Mr. Mutiso informed him that he, Mr. Mutiso, intends to sell all his Land in Uganda, }{\insrsid788741\charrsid31649 
including the suit property, }{\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649 all that Mr. Mutiso states in reply is that the property sought to be preserved is not his.  He does }{\insrsid31649\charrsid31649 not deny}{\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649  }{
\insrsid788741\charrsid31649 or admit }{\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649 giving information to Mr. Kasenge about the intended sale}{\insrsid788741\charrsid31649  or how he came to be linked with it}{\insrsid13924983\charrsid31649 .
\par }{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 
\par I consider this to be a material omission in Mr. Mutiso\rquote s affidavit, presumably deliberate.
\par 
\par The genesis of the applicant\rquote s concerns about the suit Lands can be gauged from the plaintiff\rquote s pleadings (plaint), para 8 thereof.   Under para 8 (vi), the plaintiff avers that upon insistence on d
ocumentary proof of the source of funds by the plaintiff, the first defendant presented to the plaintiff a document that purported to be a lease agreement between the 2}{\super\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 nd}{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 
 defendant and one Blue Field Associates for land comprised in Block 491, Plot 2 at Kiziba, Kyaggwe.  It is averred that the document was executed by the 1}{\super\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 st}{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 
 defendant on behalf of the 2}{\super\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 nd}{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649  defendant on one hand and the 5}{\super\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 th}{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 
 defendant as an agent of Blue Field Associates on the other hand.  The lease agreement is attached to the plaint.
\par }{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 
\par }{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 It is noteworthy }{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 again }{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 that the plaintiff\rquote s }{\insrsid1534473\charrsid31649 case}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  against the defendants is that the 1}
{\super\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 st}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  defendant banked a forged bank draft in favour of the 2}{\super\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 nd}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 
 defendant with the plaintiff/applicant for USD 400.000 and that upon trusting the documents that the first defendant produced before the plaintiff to }{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 prove}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 
 the source of funds, the plaintiff paid the 1}{\super\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 st}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  and 2}{\super\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 nd}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  defendants USD 385,914.61.  The plaintiff\rquote 
s case is that the draft bounced }{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 after}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  the defendants }{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 had taken}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  the money }{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 on }{
\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 it}{\insrsid7696563\charrsid31649 .}{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649  }{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  Trusting as I do that the question
 whether or not a plaint discloses a cause of action must be determined upon perusal of the plaint alone and anything attached as to form part of it, it is clear to me that the plaintiff\rquote s pleadings do sufficiently link the 1}{
\super\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649 st}{\insrsid9466393\charrsid31649  defendant with the bank draf
t that bounced and the suit property herein.  For this reason alone, I would think that the plaintiff is entitled to an order that would preserve the suit property pending determination of the main suit.  In an application under 0.41 r. 1, it must essenti
a
lly be shown that the property in dispute is in danger of being wasted, damaged or alienated by any party to the suit.  It would appear to me that such party need not be the registered owner thereof to be prevented from disposing of it during the pendancy
 
of the suit.  In my view, if an order such as the one sought herein is granted and the real owner shows up and wants to dispose of the suit property in exercise of his rights as owner, whether or not such owner is party to the proceedings, he can still be
 heard by Court in the matter with a view to discharging the property from the order.  In the circumstances of this case, I see no reason to }{\insrsid5784199\charrsid31649 deny granting the order sought herein.}{\insrsid16072392\charrsid31649 
\par }{\insrsid5784199\charrsid31649 
\par I note that grant of a temporary injunction is a matter within the discretio
n of Court.  The discretion must of course be exercised judicially.  The applicant must show that he/she has a prima facie case with a probability of success; and that the applicant might otherwise suffer irreparable damage which would not be adequately c
ompensated in damages.  
\par 
\par If the Court is in doubt on any of the above two issues, it will decide the application on a balance of convenience.  The purpose of an application for a temporary injunction}{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 
 should in the first instance be to preserve the status quo.}{\insrsid5784199\charrsid31649 
\par }{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 
\par Applying the above principles to the }{\insrsid87354\charrsid31649 instant case}{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 , especially as to whether or not the applicant has a prima facie case with a probability of }{\insrsid31649\charrsid31649 success;}{
\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649  Court is not concerned with whether or not the claim is frivolous or vexatio}{\insrsid16136311\charrsid31649 u}{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 s.  That, I think, can await the hearing of the suit.  The Court\rquote 
s concern at this stage is whether or not there is a serious question to be tried.  Form the pleadings, such a question exists.
\par 
\par As to whether the applicant might suffer irreparable damage which would not be adequately compensated in damages, Court is in some doubt.  There is no evidence of how much property}{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649 , if any, }{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 
the defendants own}{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649  in Uganda}{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 .  }{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649 H}{\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 owever, Court has been told that the 1}{\super\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 st}{
\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649  defendant, thought to be the brain behind the alleged fraud, is a foreigner.  It has not been denied that he, the first defendant, has intimated to Mr. Kasenge th}{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649 e plans}{
\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649  to}{\insrsid15539332\charrsid31649  sell the suit property.  }{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649 1}{\super\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649 st}{\insrsid1316938\charrsid31649  defendant}{\insrsid15539332\charrsid31649 
 has denied ownership of the property, implying that he personally does not stand to lose anything or suffer any inconvenie
nce in the event that any intended sale or alienation is put on hold pending determination of the suit.  The balance of convenience is therefore in favour of granting the }{\insrsid9333776\charrsid31649 order sought.}{\insrsid1071381\charrsid31649 
  I hasten to add that one property, Block 491 Plot 2 at Kiziba, Kyaggwe, is stated in the plaint as linked to the alleged fraudulent deal.  }{\insrsid16136311\charrsid31649 However,}{\insrsid1071381\charrsid31649  sufficient }{
\insrsid16136311\charrsid31649 ground}{\insrsid1071381\charrsid31649  has been }{\insrsid16136311\charrsid31649 given}{\insrsid1071381\charrsid31649 
 in this application to warrant encumbering Singo Block 293 Plot 47 Land at Myanzi as well.  The same shall be }{\insrsid16136311\charrsid31649 included in}{\insrsid1071381\charrsid31649  the order herein}{\insrsid16136311\charrsid31649 .}{
\insrsid14710938\charrsid31649 
\par }{\insrsid9333776\charrsid31649 
\par In t
he final result, Court is satisfied that the purpose of this application is to maintain the status quo pending determination of the suit.  On perusal of all available records, I have come to the conclusion that the applicant has brought itself within the 
scope of the law under which applications for temporary injunctions are granted.  I allow the application and grant the order sought.  Costs herein shall abide the outcome of the main suit.
